description: Attested since the 1540s; Latin praestigiosus (“full of tricks”), praestigiae (“juggler's tricks”), possibly an alteration of praestringō (“to blindfold, to dazzle”), from prae- (“before”) with stringō (“to bind or tie”); equivalent to prestige +‎ -ous. Unstressed /ɛ/ is retained by analogy with prestige.

adjectives.description: prestigious (comparative more prestigious, superlative most prestigious)

examples: She has a prestigious job with an international organization.
